I"„<p><img src="/assets/img/python/termgraph.jpg" alt="Termgraph - draw graphics on the terminal" /></p>

<p>Several <a href="https://en.terminalroot.com.br/hello-world-in-25-programming-languages-proposal-docs-and-links/">programming languages</a> are available for creating graphics and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_visualization">visualizing data</a>. <a href="https://en.terminalroot.com.br/basic-python-script-for-learning/">Python</a> is one of the ‚Äú<a href="https://en.terminalroot.com.br/the-30-best-python-libraries-and-packages-for-beginners/">richest</a>‚Äù libraries in this regard, <a href="https://en.terminalroot.com.br/the-30-best-python-libraries-and-packages-for-beginners/">matplotlib</a> is one of the most used. The <a href="https://www.r-project.org/">R programming language</a> is also one of the best in this regard and we can mention <strong>ggplot2</strong>.</p>

<p>But what if you are looking for an even faster and easier way to view data stored in a plain text file. And maybe you don‚Äôt want to leave the comfort of the terminal? You may be interested in <strong>Termgraph</strong>.</p>

